Can you imagine how it must be to live in an all pedestrian town where there
are virtually no cars? Such a place does exist, and it's called [La
Cumbrecita](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Cumbrecita) (The Little Peak).
The small town is located just 120 kilometers (75 miles) from the Argentinian
city of [CÃ³rdoba](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%C3%B3rdoba,_Argentina), in
Sierras Grandes in the province of CÃ³rdoba, and it has roughly 1,000
residents.

La Cumbrecita is a gem of ecotourism with an aesthetic that recalls a 15th
century German town. It was founded less than a century ago, according to the
province government's [tourist
website](http://www.cordobaturismo.gov.ar/localidad/la-cumbrecita/):

> En el aÃ±o 1932, viaja a Argentina desde Alemania el Dr. Helmut Cabjolsky
> acompaÃ±ado por su familia. En la bÃºsqueda de un lugar para vacacionar,
> compra en 1934 en las sierras de CÃ³rdoba un campo de aproximadamente 500 ha,
> el cual contenÃ­a como punto de referencia geogrÃ¡fico al denominado Cerro
> Cumbrecita.
>
> La primera edificaciÃ³n [era para servir] de casa de veraneo para la familia
> Cabjolsky, pero muy pronto se transformÃ³ en albergue para alojar a los
> amigos de la familia. AÃ±os mÃ¡s tarde, dado el creciente interÃ©s turÃ­stico
> que despertaba el territorio, la casa comenzÃ³ a funcionar como una pequeÃ±a
> hosterÃ­a.

> Back in 1932, Dr. Helmut Cabjolsky went to Argentina from Germany together
> with his family. They were looking for a place to spend their vacations, so
> in 1934 he bought a 500-hectare land in the CÃ³rdoba mountains that had as
> geographical landmark: the so-called Cumbrecita hill.
>
> The first building [was meant to be used] as summer house for the
> Cabjolskys, but soon after it became a guest house for family friends. Years
> later, due to the increasing tourist interest in the place, the house
> started to operate as a small hostel.

At first, the town wasn't designed as the [tourist
destination](http://www.turismocordoba.com.ar/lacumbrecita/historia.php) that
it has now become:

> La divulgaciÃ³n del encanto del lugar [â€¦] no fue intencional sino mÃ¡s bien
> circunstancial y de boca en boca, ya que nunca se habÃ­a pensado en la
> posibilidad de que La Cumbrecita, CÃ³rdoba, podrÃ­a transformarse en polo de
> atracciÃ³n turÃ­stica.
>
> En la actualidad, el turismo en La Cumbrecita, CÃ³rdoba, es uno de los
> mayores atractivos de la regiÃ³n, llenando sus calles de visitantes
> nacionales e internacionales durante cada temporada estival.

> As the place's charm spread by word of mouth [â€¦] the possibility of La
> Cumbrecita, CÃ³rdoba, becoming a tourist destination wasn't our intention,
> but rather circumstantial.
>
> Today, La Cumbrecita, CÃ³rdoba, is one of the most attractive tourist places
> in the region. Every summer season its streets are always filled with
